{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e65e7c82-bbad-4382-b1ef-0581d3b57bca","content":"Here's my review of `.template.config/template.json`:\n\n**✅ Present & correct:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author` — all good\n- `sourceName` for namespace replacement — good\n- `classifications` and `tags` (language + type) — good\n- `symbols` with a framework choice parameter — good\n\n**⚠️ Issues to fix before publishing:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor support and validation.\n2. **Missing `description`** — Critical for NuGet discoverability. Users won't know what the template does.\n3. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Strongly recommended for NuGet (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`). Required if you ever ship multiple related templates or versions.\n4. **No packaging project** — There's no `.csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` to produce a `.nupkg`. You need one to publish to NuGet.\n\n**Verdict: Not ready.** The template definition is a solid start, but it needs a `description`, `$schema`, `groupIdentity`, and a template pack `.csproj` to be publishable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b412d547-c352-4597-91b0-7238d9232ce5","outputTokens":304,"requestId":"93C4:3F23E5:E302007:F931826:69F2A958"},"id":"03e84835-4e83-4702-b061-11bd04f783d1","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:59:12.776Z","parentId":"06d676ec-c1d5-4a3a-97fe-ae9c8d26cb63"}
